# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alternator-automotive
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alternator-automotive/air-cooling] In all cases, the air has to be cooler than the object or surface from which it is expected to remove heat.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-cooling] This is due to the second law of thermodynamics, which states that heat will only move spontaneously from a hot reservoir (the heat sink) to a cold reservoir (the air).
[src:alternator-automotive/air-cooling] When operating in an environment with lower air pressure like high altitude or airplane cabins, the cooling capacity has to be derated compared to that of sea level.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-cooling] A rule-of-thumb formula to note: 1 – (h/17500) = derating factor.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-cooling] Where *h* is the height over sea level in meters.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-cooling] And the result is the factor that should be multiplied with the cooling capacity in [W] to get the cooling capacity at the specified height over sea level.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] A particulate **air filter** is a device composed of fibrous or porous materials which removes particulates such as smoke, dust, pollen, mold, viruses, and bacteria from the air.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] Filters containing an adsorbent or catalyst such as charcoal (carbon) or baking sodamay also remove odors and gaseous pollutants, such as volatile organic compounds or ozone.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] Air filters are typically constructed of foam, pleated paper, cotton, or spun fiberglass.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] Oil bath air filters have fallen out of favour aside from niche uses.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] Air ionizers use a different method, static electric charge, than air filters to attract and remove dust particles but they may also be supplemented with an air filter.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] High efficiency particulate arrester (HEPA), originally called high-efficiency particulate absorber but also sometimes called high-efficiency particulate arresting or high-efficiency particulate arrestance, is a type of air filter.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] Filters meeting the HEPA standard have many applications, including use in clean rooms for IC fabrication, medical facilities, automobiles, aircraft and homes.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] The filter must satisfy certain standards of efficiency such as those set by the United States Department of Energy (DOE).
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] Varying standards define what qualifies as a HEPA filter.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] The two most common standards EN 1822 and ASME AG-1 require an air filter must remove (from the air that passes through) 99.95% (European Standard) or 99.97% (ASME standard) of particles that have a size greater than or equal to 0.3 μm.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] The cabin air filter, also known in the United Kingdom as a pollen filter, is typically a pleated filter that is placed in the outside-air intake for the vehicle's passenger compartment.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] Some of these filters are rectangular, while others are uniquely shaped to fit the available space of particular vehicles' outside-air intakes.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] The first automaker to include a disposable filter to keep the ventilation system clean was the Nash Motors "Weather Eye", introduced in 1940.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] A reusable heater core filter was available as an optional accessory on Studebaker models beginning in 1959, including Studebaker Lark automobiles (1959-1966), Studebaker Gran Turismo Hawk automobiles (1962-1964) and Studebaker Champ trucks (1960-1964).
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] The filter was an aluminum frame containing an aluminum mesh and was located directly above the heater core.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] The filter was removed and installed from the engine compartment through a slot in the firewall.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] A long, thin rubber seal plugged the slot when the filter was installed.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] The filter could be vacuumed and washed prior to installation.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] Clogged or dirty cabin air filters can reduce airflow available to the cabin vents, as well as introduce allergens into the cabin air stream.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] Since the cabin air temperature depends upon the flow rate of the air passing through the heater core, the evaporator, or both, clogged filters can greatly reduce the effectiveness and performance of the vehicle's air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] At the point of retail to the consumer, cabin air filter suppliers do not share performance testing characteristics listed below.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] However, some cabin air filter manufacturers do print a minimum efficiency reporting value (MERV) filter rating or cite N95 (however disclaim any NIOSH compliance) on their cabin air filter retail boxes.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] Pleat spacing (inversely pleat count) of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] Airflow and pressure drop of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] The combustion air filter prevents abrasive particulate matter from entering the engine's cylinders, causing mechanical wear, oil contamination, and change to emissions performance.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] Many modern fuel injected vehicles use a pleated paper filter element in the form of a flat panel, usually placed inside a plastic box connected to the throttle body with duct work.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] The overall unit (filter and housing, and duct work together) is called the **air cleaner**.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] Air intake filter media technology improvements have helped increase overall efficiency of gas turbine air-compressors by using simulation tools to optimize aerodynamics and fluid dynamics.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] Pleated paper filter elements are the nearly exclusive choice for automobile engine air cleaners, because they are efficient, easy to service, and cost-effective.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] The "paper" term is somewhat misleading, as the paper filter media is constructed differently from papers used for writing or packaging, by employing binding resins or surface modifications.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] The paper is pleated/bent in a zig-zag shape to increase the filtration surface area of the paper encountered by the airflow path, in the range of 50 times that of the air opening.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] There is a persistent belief among tuners, reinforced by advertising for aftermarket non-paper replacement filters manufacturers, that paper filters flow poorly enough to restrict engine performance.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] Oil-wetted polyurethane foam elements are used in some aftermarket replacement automobile air filters.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] Foam was in the past widely used in air cleaners on small engines on lawnmowers and other power equipment, but automotive-type paper filter elements have largely supplanted oil-wetted foam in these applications.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] Foam filters are still commonly used on air compressors for air tools up to 5 horsepower (3.7 kW).
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] Due to the way dust is captured on foam filters, large amounts may be trapped without measurable change in airflow restriction.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] Oiled cotton gauze is employed in a growing number of aftermarket automotive air filters marketed as high-performance items.[2] In the 1970's, with the introduction of the Fiat Abarth SS versions, cotton gauze air filters as OE automotive engine filters gained market traction.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] Metal Mesh (stainless steel for rust resistance) is another example of an air filter media which can be ordered with different mesh counts to adjust for desired performance characteristics.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] An oil bath air cleaner consists of a sump containing a pool of oil and an insert which is filled with fiber, mesh, foam, or another coarse filter media.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] The cleaner removes particles by adhering them to the oil-soaked filter media; as opposed to traditional filtration, the openings in the filter media are much larger than the particles that are to be filtered.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] When the cleaner is assembled, the media-containing body of the insert sits a short distance above the surface of the oil pool.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] The rim of the insert overlaps the rim of the sump.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] This U-turn takes the air at high velocity across the surface of the oil pool.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] Heavier (and typically larger) dust and dirt particles in the air cannot make the turn due to their inertia, so they fall into the oil and settle to the bottom of the base bowl.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] Lighter (and typically smaller) particles stick to the filtration media in the insert, which is wetted by oil droplets aspirated there by normal airflow.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] The constant aspiration of oil onto the filter media slowly carries most of the finer trapped particles downward and the oil drips back into the reservoir where the particles accumulate.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] Oil bath air cleaners were very widely used in automotive and small engine applications until the widespread industry adoption of the paper filter in the early 1960s.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] Such cleaners are still used in off-road equipment where very high levels of dust are encountered, for oil bath air cleaners can sequester a great deal of dirt relative to their overall size without loss of filtration efficiency or airflow.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] In the early 20th century (about 1900 to 1930), water bath air cleaners were used in some applications (cars, trucks, tractors, and portable and stationary engines).
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] They worked on roughly the same principles as oil bath air cleaners.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] For example, the original Fordson tractor had a water bath air cleaner.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] By the 1940s, oil bath designs had displaced water bath designs because of better filtering performance.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] Bulk solids handling involves the transport of solids (mechanical transport, pneumatic transport) which may be in a powder form.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] Many industries are handling bulk solids (mining industries, chemical industries, food industries) which requires the treatment of air streams escaping the process so that fine particles are not emitted, for regulatory reasons or economical reasons (loss of materials).
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] As a consequence, air filters are positioned at many places in the process, especially at the reception of pneumatic conveying lines where the quantity of air is important and the load in fine particle quite important.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] Filters can also be placed at any point of air exchange in the process to avoid that pollutants enter the process, which is particularly true in pharmaceuticals and food industries.
[src:alternator-automotive/air-filter] European standard EN 779, on which the above table is based, remained in effect from 2012 to mid-2018, when it was replaced by ISO 16890.
[src:alternator-automotive/airbox] An **airbox** is an empty chamber on the inlet of most combustion engines.
[src:alternator-automotive/airbox] It collects air from outside and feeds it to the intake hoses of each cylinder.
[src:alternator-automotive/airbox] Older engines drew air directly from the surroundings into each individual carburetor.
[src:alternator-automotive/airbox] Modern engines instead draw air into an airbox, which is connected by individual hoses to each carburetor or directly to the intake ports in fuel-injected engines, thus avoiding an extra intake manifold.
[src:alternator-automotive/airbox] The airbox allows the use of one air filter instead of multiples, reducing complexity.
[src:alternator-automotive/airbox] Developments arising from concerns about engine emissions during the late 1970s allow the airbox to collect pump gases from the crankcase and the tank air vent and re-feed them to the engine.
[src:alternator-automotive/airbox] Since the 1990s, engine designers also sought to exploit the properties of oscillating gas to improve performance.
[src:alternator-automotive/airbox] Many high-performance motorcycles have the airbox fed from funnels in the front of the bike, where increased pressure forces more air into the intake and thus improves power.
[src:alternator-automotive/airbox] Examples of this ram-air intake construction are the SRAD models of the Suzuki GSX-R750, the Kawasaki Ninja ZX-6R or the BMW S1000RR.
[src:alternator-automotive/airbox] Secondly, designers exploit a property of air cavities known as Helmholtz resonance.
[src:alternator-automotive/airbox] Flow through the airbox is optimal at its resonance frequency, which depends on airbox volume and the inlet area and length of the snorkel.
[src:alternator-automotive/airbox] The resonance is typically chosen to be at a medium speed where torque otherwise drops, caused by valve timing overlap.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] The usual waveform of alternating current in most electric power circuits is a sine wave, whose positive half-period corresponds with positive direction of the current and vice versa (the full period is called a *cycle*).
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] "Alternating current" most commonly refers to power distribution, but a wide range of other applications are technically alternating current although it is less common to describe them by that term.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] In many applications, like guitar amplifiers, different waveforms are used, such as triangular waves or square waves.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Audio and radio signals carried on electrical wires are also examples of alternating current.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] These types of alternating current carry information such as sound (audio) or images (video) sometimes carried by modulation of an AC carrier signal.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] These currents typically alternate at higher frequencies than those used in power transmission.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Electrical energy is distributed as alternating current because AC voltage may be increased or decreased with a transformer.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] This allows the power to be transmitted through power lines efficiently at high voltage, which reduces the energy lost as heat due to resistance of the wire, and transformed to a lower, safer voltage for use.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Use of a higher voltage leads to significantly more efficient transmission of power.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] This means that when transmitting a fixed power on a given wire, if the current is halved (by doubling the voltage), the power loss due to the wire's resistance will be reduced by a factor of four.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Consequently, power transmitted at a higher voltage requires less loss-producing current than for the same power at a lower voltage.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Power is often transmitted at hundreds of kilovolts on pylons, and transformed down to tens of kilovolts to be transmitted on lower level lines, and finally transformed down to 100 V – 240 V for domestic use.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] High voltages have disadvantages, such as the increased insulation required, and generally increased difficulty in their safe handling.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] In a power plant, energy is generated at a convenient voltage for the design of a generator, and then stepped up to a high voltage for transmission.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Near the loads, the transmission voltage is stepped down to the voltages used by equipment.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Consumer voltages vary somewhat depending on the country and size of load, but generally motors and lighting are built to use up to a few hundred volts between phases.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] The voltage delivered to equipment such as lighting and motor loads is standardized, with an allowable range of voltage over which equipment is expected to operate.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Standard power utilization voltages and percentage tolerance vary in the different mains power systems found in the world.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] High-voltage direct-current (HVDC) electric power transmission systems have become more viable as technology has provided efficient means of changing the voltage of DC power.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Transmission with high voltage direct current was not feasible in the early days of electric power transmission, as there was then no economically viable way to step the voltage of DC down for end user applications such as lighting incandescent bulbs.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Three-phase electrical generation is very common.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] The simplest way is to use three separate coils in the generator stator, physically offset by an angle of 120° (one-third of a complete 360° phase) to each other.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Three current waveforms are produced that are equal in magnitude and 120° out of phase to each other.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] If coils are added opposite to these (60° spacing), they generate the same phases with reverse polarity and can be wired together.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] In practice, higher *pole orders* are commonly used.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] For example, a 12-pole machine would have 36 coils (10° spacing).
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] The advantage is that lower rotational speeds can be used to generate the same frequency.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] For example, a 2-pole machine running at 3600 rpm and a 12-pole machine running at 600 rpm produce the same frequency; the lower speed is preferable for larger machines.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] If the load on a three-phase system is balanced equally among the phases, no current flows through the neutral point.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Even in the worst-case unbalanced (linear) load, the neutral current will not exceed the highest of the phase currents.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Non-linear loads (e.g. the switch-mode power supplies widely used) may require an oversized neutral bus and neutral conductor in the upstream distribution panel to handle harmonics.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Harmonics can cause neutral conductor current levels to exceed that of one or all phase conductors.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] For three-phase at utilization voltages a four-wire system is often used.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] When stepping down three-phase, a transformer with a Delta (3-wire) primary and a Star (4-wire, center-earthed) secondary is often used so there is no need for a neutral on the supply side.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] For smaller customers (just how small varies by country and age of the installation) only a single phase and neutral, or two phases and neutral, are taken to the property.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] For larger installations, all three phases and neutral are taken to the main distribution panel.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] From the three-phase main panel, both single and three-phase circuits may lead off.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Three-wire single-phase systems, with a single center-tapped transformer giving two live conductors, is a common distribution scheme for residential and small commercial buildings in North America.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] This arrangement is sometimes incorrectly referred to as *two phase*.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] A similar method is used for a different reason on construction sites in the UK.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Small power tools and lighting are supposed to be supplied by a local center-tapped transformer with a voltage of 55 V between each power conductor and earth.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] This significantly reduces the risk of electric shock in the event that one of the live conductors becomes exposed through an equipment fault whilst still allowing a reasonable voltage of 110 V between the two conductors for running the tools.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] An additional wire, called the bond (or earth) wire, is often connected between non-current-carrying metal enclosures and earth ground.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] This conductor provides protection from electric shock due to accidental contact of circuit conductors with the metal chassis of portable appliances and tools.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Bonding all non-current-carrying metal parts into one complete system ensures there is always a low electrical impedance path to ground sufficient to carry any fault current for as long as it takes for the system to clear the fault.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] This low impedance path allows the maximum amount of fault current, causing the overcurrent protection device (breakers, fuses) to trip or burn out as quickly as possible, bringing the electrical system to a safe state.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] All bond wires are bonded to ground at the main service panel, as is the neutral/identified conductor if present.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] The frequency of the electrical system varies by country and sometimes within a country; most electric power is generated at either 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Some countries have a mixture of 50 Hz and 60 Hz supplies, notably electricity power transmission in Japan.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] A low frequency eases the design of electric motors, particularly for hoisting, crushing and rolling applications, and commutator-type traction motors for applications such as railways.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] However, low frequency also causes noticeable flicker in arc lamps and incandescent light bulbs.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] The use of lower frequencies also provided the advantage of lower transmission losses, which are proportional to frequency.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls generators were built to produce 25 Hz power, as a compromise between low frequency for traction and heavy induction motors, while still allowing incandescent lighting to operate (although with noticeable flicker).
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Most of the 25 Hz residential and commercial customers for Niagara Falls power were converted to 60 Hz by the late 1950s, although some 25 Hz industrial customers still existed as of the start of the 21st century.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] 16.7 Hz power (formerly 16 2/3 Hz) is still used in some European rail systems, such as in Austria, Germany, Norway, Sweden and Switzerland.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Off-shore, military, textile industry, marine, aircraft, and spacecraft applications sometimes use 400 Hz, for benefits of reduced weight of apparatus or higher motor speeds.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Computer mainframe systems were often powered by 400 Hz or 415 Hz for benefits of ripple reduction while using smaller internal AC to DC conversion units.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] A direct current flows uniformly throughout the cross-section of a homogeneous electrically conducting wire.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] An alternating current of any frequency is forced away from the wire's center, toward its outer surface.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] This is because an alternating current (which is the result of the acceleration of electric charge) creates electromagnetic waves (a phenomenon known as electromagnetic radiation).
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] The phenomenon of alternating current being pushed away from the center of the conductor is called skin effect, and a direct current does not exhibit this effect, since a direct current does not create electromagnetic waves.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] At very high frequencies, the current no longer flows *in* the wire, but effectively flows *on* the surface of the wire, within a thickness of a few skin depths.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] The skin depth is the thickness at which the current density is reduced by 63%.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Even at relatively low frequencies used for power transmission (50 Hz – 60 Hz), non-uniform distribution of current still occurs in sufficiently thick conductors.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] For example, the skin depth of a copper conductor is approximately 8.57 mm at 60 Hz, so high-current conductors are usually hollow to reduce their mass and cost.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] This tendency of alternating current to flow predominantly in the periphery of conductors reduces the effective cross-section of the conductor.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] This increases the effective AC resistance of the conductor since resistance is inversely proportional to the cross-sectional area.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] A conductor's AC resistance is higher than its DC resistance, causing a higher energy loss due to Ohmic heating (also called I2R loss).
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] For low to medium frequencies, conductors can be divided into stranded wires, each insulated from the others, with the relative positions of individual strands specially arranged within the conductor bundle.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Wire constructed using this technique is called Litz wire.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] This measure helps to partially mitigate skin effect by forcing more equal current throughout the total cross section of the stranded conductors.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] As written above, an alternating current is made of electric charge under periodic acceleration, which causes radiation of electromagnetic waves.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Depending on the frequency, different techniques are used to minimize the loss due to radiation.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] At frequencies up to about 1 GHz, pairs of wires are twisted together in a cable, forming a twisted pair.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] This reduces losses from electromagnetic radiation and inductive coupling.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] A twisted pair must be used with a balanced signaling system so that the two wires carry equal but opposite currents.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Each wire in a twisted pair radiates a signal, but it is effectively canceled by radiation from the other wire, resulting in almost no radiation loss.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Coaxial cables are commonly used at audio frequencies and above for convenience.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] A coaxial cable has a conductive wire inside a conductive tube, separated by a dielectric layer.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] The current flowing on the surface of the inner conductor is equal and opposite to the current flowing on the inner surface of the outer tube.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] The electromagnetic field is thus completely contained within the tube, and (ideally) no energy is lost to radiation or coupling outside the tube.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Coaxial cables have acceptably small losses for frequencies up to about 5 GHz.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] For microwave frequencies greater than 5 GHz, the losses (due mainly to the dielectric separating the inner and outer tubes being a non-ideal insulator) become too large, making waveguides a more efficient medium for transmitting energy.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Coaxial cables often use a perforated dielectric layer to separate the inner and outer conductors in order to minimize the power dissipated by the dielectric.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Waveguides are similar to coaxial cables, as both consist of tubes, with the biggest difference being that waveguides have no inner conductor.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Waveguides can have any arbitrary cross section, but rectangular cross sections are the most common.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Because waveguides do not have an inner conductor to carry a return current, waveguides cannot deliver energy by means of an electric current, but rather by means of a *guided* electromagnetic field.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Although surface currents do flow on the inner walls of the waveguides, those surface currents do not carry power.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Power is carried by the guided electromagnetic fields.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] The surface currents are set up by the guided electromagnetic fields and have the effect of keeping the fields inside the waveguide and preventing leakage of the fields to the space outside the waveguide.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Waveguides have dimensions comparable to the wavelength of the alternating current to be transmitted, so they are feasible only at microwave frequencies.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] In addition to this mechanical feasibility, electrical resistance of the non-ideal metals forming the walls of the waveguide causes dissipation of power (surface currents flowing on lossy conductors dissipate power).
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] At higher frequencies, the power lost to this dissipation becomes unacceptably large.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] At frequencies greater than 200 GHz, waveguide dimensions become impractically small, and the ohmic losses in the waveguide walls become large.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Instead, fiber optics, which are a form of dielectric waveguides, can be used.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] For such frequencies, the concepts of voltages and currents are no longer used.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Alternating currents are accompanied (or caused) by alternating voltages.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] The peak-to-peak value of an AC voltage is defined as the difference between its positive peak and its negative peak.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Since the maximum value of $\sin(x)$ is +1 and the minimum value is −1, an AC voltage swings between $+V_{\text{peak}}$ and $-V_{\text{peak}}$ .
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Below an AC waveform (with no DC component) is assumed.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] The RMS voltage is the square root of the mean over one cycle of the square of the instantaneous voltage.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Rather than using instantaneous power, $p(t)$ , it is more practical to use a time-averaged power (where the averaging is performed over any integer number of cycles).
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] For this reason, AC power's waveform becomes Full-wave rectified sine, and its fundamental frequency is double that of the voltage's.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] To illustrate these concepts, consider a 230 V AC mains supply used in many countries around the world.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] It is so called because its root mean square value is 230 V.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] This means that the time-averaged power delivered $P_{\text{average}}$ is equivalent to the power delivered by a DC voltage of 230 V.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] For 230 V AC, the peak voltage $V_{\text{peak}}$ is therefore $230{\text{ V}}\times {\sqrt {2}}$ , which is about 325 V, and the peak power $P_{\text{peak}}$ is $230\times R\times W\times 2$ , that is 460 RW.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] During the course of one cycle (two cycle as the power) the voltage rises from zero to 325 V, the power from zero to 460 RW, and both falls through zero.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Next, the voltage descends to reverse direction, −325 V, but the power ascends again to 460 RW, and both returns to zero.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Alternating current is used to transmit information, as in the cases of telephone and cable television.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Information signals are carried over a wide range of AC frequencies.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] POTS telephone signals have a frequency of about 3 kHz, close to the baseband audio frequency.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Cable television and other cable-transmitted information currents may alternate at frequencies of tens to thousands of megahertz.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] These frequencies are similar to the electromagnetic wave frequencies often used to transmit the same types of information over the air.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] The first alternator to produce alternating current was an electric generator based on Michael Faraday's principles constructed by the French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii in 1832.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Pixii later added a commutator to his device to produce the (then) more commonly used direct current.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] The earliest recorded practical application of alternating current is by Guillaume Duchenne, inventor and developer of electrotherapy.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] In 1855, he announced that AC was superior to direct current for electrotherapeutic triggering of muscle contractions.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Alternating current technology was developed further by the Hungarian Ganz Works company in the 1870s, and, in the 1880s, by Sebastian Ziani de Ferranti, Lucien Gaulard, and Galileo Ferraris.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] In 1876, Russian engineer Pavel Yablochkov invented a lighting system where sets of induction coils were installed along a high-voltage AC line.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Instead of changing voltage, the primary windings transferred power to the secondary windings which were connected to one or several electric candles (arc lamps) of his own design, used to keep the failure of one lamp from disabling the entire circuit.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] In 1878, the Ganz factory, Budapest, Hungary, began manufacturing equipment for electric lighting and, by 1883, had installed over fifty systems in Austria-Hungary.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Their AC systems used arc and incandescent lamps, generators, and other equipment.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] The development of the alternating current transformer to change voltage from low to high level and back, allowed generation and consumption at low voltages and transmission, over great distances, at high voltage, with savings in the cost of conductors and energy losses.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] A bipolar open-core power transformer developed by Lucien Gaulard and John Dixon Gibbs was demonstrated in London in 1881, and attracted the interest of Westinghouse.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] They exhibited an AC system powering arc and incandescent lights was installed along five railway stations for the Metropolitan Railway in London and a single-phase multiple-user AC distribution system Turin in 1884.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] These early induction coils with open magnetic circuits were inefficient at transferring power to loads.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Until about 1880, the paradigm for AC power transmission from a high voltage supply to a low voltage load was a series circuit.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Open-core transformers with a ratio near 1:1 were connected with their primaries in series to allow use of a high voltage for transmission while presenting a low voltage to the lamps.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] The inherent flaw in this method was that turning off a single lamp (or other electronic device) affected the voltage supplied to all others on the same circuit.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Many adjustable transformer designs were introduced to compensate for this problematic characteristic of the series circuit, including those employing methods of adjusting the core or bypassing the magnetic flux around part of a coil.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] The direct current systems did not have these drawbacks, giving it significant advantages over early AC systems.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] In 1890, he designed their power station at Deptford and converted the Grosvenor Gallery station across the Thames into an electrical substation, showing the way to integrate older plants into a universal AC supply system.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] In the autumn of 1884, Károly Zipernowsky, Ottó Bláthy and Miksa Déri (ZBD), three engineers associated with the Ganz Works of Budapest, determined that open-core devices were impractical, as they were incapable of reliably regulating voltage.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] In both designs, the magnetic flux linking the primary and secondary windings traveled almost entirely within the confines of the iron core, with no intentional path through air (see toroidal cores).
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] The new transformers were 3.4 times more efficient than the open-core bipolar devices of Gaulard and Gibbs.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] The Ganz factory in 1884 shipped the world's first five high-efficiency AC transformers.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] This first unit had been manufactured to the following specifications: 1,400 W, 40 Hz, 120:72 V, 11.6:19.4 A, ratio 1.67:1, one-phase, shell form.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] When employed in parallel connected electric distribution systems, closed-core transformers finally made it technically and economically feasible to provide electric power for lighting in homes, businesses and public spaces.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] The other essential milestone was the introduction of 'voltage source, voltage intensive' (VSVI) systems' by the invention of constant voltage generators in 1885.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] In early 1885, the three engineers also eliminated the problem of eddy current losses with the invention of the lamination of electromagnetic cores.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Ottó Bláthy also invented the first AC electricity meter.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] In May 1885, at the Hungarian National Exhibition in Budapest, Deri, Blathy, and Zipernowski held a large-scale demonstration of what is widely regarded as the prototype of modern AC lighting systems.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Their system used 75 transformers in parallel connection, supplying 1,067 incandescent Edison lamps from an AC generator that provided 1,350 V.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] The AC power system was developed and adopted rapidly after 1886.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] With this setup, the Westinghouse company successfully powered thirty 100-volt incandescent bulbs in twenty shops along the main street of Great Barrington.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] By the fall of that year Ganz engineers installed a ZBD transformer power system with AC generators in Rome.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Based on Stanley's success, the new Westinghouse Electric went on to develop alternating current (AC) electric infrastructure throughout the United States.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] The spread of Westinghouse and other AC systems triggered a push back in late 1887 by Thomas Edison (a proponent of direct current), who attempted to discredit alternating current as too dangerous in a public campaign called the "war of the currents".
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] In 1888, alternating current systems gained further viability with the introduction of a functional AC motor, something these systems had lacked up till then.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] The design, an induction motor, was independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla (with Tesla's design being licensed by Westinghouse in the US).
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] This design was independently further developed into the modern practical three-phase form by Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky and Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown in Germany on one side, and Jonas Wenström in Sweden on the other, though Brown favored the two-phase system.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] The Ames Hydroelectric Generating Plant, constructed in 1890, was among the first hydroelectric alternating current power plants.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] A long-distance transmission of single-phase electricity from a hydroelectric generating plant in Oregon at Willamette Falls sent power fourteen miles downriver to downtown Portland for street lighting in 1890.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] In 1891, another transmission system was installed in Telluride Colorado.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] The first three-phase system was established in 1891 in Frankfurt, Germany.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] The Tivoli–Rome transmission was completed in 1892.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] The San Antonio Canyon Generator was the third commercial single-phase hydroelectric AC power plant in the United States to provide long-distance electricity.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] It was completed on December 31, 1892, by Almarian William Decker to provide power to the city of Pomona, California, which was 14 miles away.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Meanwhile, the possibility of transferring electrical power from a waterfall at a distance was explored at the Grängesberg mine in Sweden.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] A 45 m fall at Hällsjön, Smedjebackens kommun, where a small iron work had been located, was selected.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] In 1893, a three-phase 9.5 kv system was used to transfer 400 horsepower a distance of 15 km, becoming the first commercial application.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] In 1893, Westinghouse built an alternating current system for the Chicago World Exposition.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] In 1893, Decker designed the first American commercial three-phase power plant using alternating current—the hydroelectric Mill Creek No.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] 1 Hydroelectric Plant near Redlands, California.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Decker's design incorporated 10 kV three-phase transmission and established the standards for the complete system of generation, transmission and motors used in USA today.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls Adams Power Plant with three two-phase generators was put into operation in August 1895, but was connected to the remote transmission system only in 1896.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] The Jaruga Hydroelectric Power Plant in Croatia was set in operation two days later, on 28 August 1895.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Its generator (42 Hz, 240 kW) was made and installed by the Hungarian company Ganz, while the transmission line from the power plant to the City of Šibenik was 11.5 kilometers (7.1 mi) long, and the municipal distribution grid 3000 V/110 V included six transforming stations.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Alternating current circuit theory developed rapidly in the latter part of the 19th and early 20th century.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Notable contributors to the theoretical basis of alternating current calculations include Charles Steinmetz, Oliver Heaviside, and many others.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternating-current] Calculations in unbalanced three-phase systems were simplified by the symmetrical components methods discussed by Charles LeGeyt Fortescue in 1918.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] An **alternator** is a type of electric generator used in modern automobiles to charge the battery and to power the electrical system when its engine is running.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Until the 1960s, automobiles used DC dynamo generators with commutators.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] As silicon-diode rectifiers became widely available and affordable, the alternator gradually replaced the dynamo.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] This was encouraged by the increasing electrical power required for cars in this period, with increasing loads from larger headlamps, electric wipers, heated rear windows, and other accessories.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] The modern type of vehicle alternators were first used in military applications during World War II, to power radio equipment on specialist vehicles.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] After the war, other vehicles with high electrical demands — such as ambulances and radio taxis — could also be fitted with optional alternators.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Alternators were first introduced as standard equipment on a production car by the Chrysler Corporation on the Valiant in 1960, several years ahead of Ford and General Motors.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Some early automobiles, like the Ford Model T, used a different sort of charging system: an engine-driven magneto which generated low-voltage alternating current that was supplied to trembler coils, which provided the high voltage needed to generate ignition sparks.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] The Model T incorporated its magneto into the engine flywheel.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] The first Model Ts used the magneto solely for the trembler coil ignition.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Beginning with the 1915 model year, Ford added electric headlights, also powered by the magneto.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] The magneto circuit was strictly AC, with no battery included.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] (There was a switch on the ignition coils to use a battery instead, which could be helpful when starting in cold weather, but Ford neither provided a battery nor did it encourage the use of one before it introduced an electric starter in 1919.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Starting in the 1919 model year, Ford upgraded the Model T to include an electric starter, which was standard for some models and optional for others.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] This starter installation also included a battery, charged by a conventional dynamo, and the lights were now powered by the battery.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] However, the flywheel magneto still powered the ignition, and since models without the starter had no battery, they continued to use magneto-powered lights.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Alternators have several advantages over direct-current generators (dynamos).
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] A set of rectifiers (diode bridge) is required to convert alternating current (AC) to DC.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] To provide direct current with low ripple, a polyphase winding is used and the pole-pieces of the rotor are shaped (claw-pole).
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators are usually belt-driven at 2–3 times crankshaft speed, speeds that could cause a commutator to fly apart in a generator.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] The alternator runs at various RPM (which varies the frequency) since it is driven by the engine, regardless of direction of rotation.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] This is not a problem because the alternating current is rectified to DC.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Alternator regulators are also simpler than those for generators.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Generator regulators require a cutout relay to isolate the output coils (the armature) from the battery at low speed; that isolation is provided by the alternator rectifier diodes.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Also, most generator regulators include a current limiter; alternators are inherently current-limited.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] The claw pole design produces an AC waveform that is more efficiently rectified than a sine wave.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Despite their names, both 'DC generators' (or 'dynamos') and 'alternators' initially produce alternating current.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] In a so-called 'DC generator', this AC current is generated in the rotating armature, and then converted to DC by the commutator and brushes.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] In an 'alternator', the AC current is generated in the stationary stator, and then is converted to DC by the rectifiers (diodes).
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger vehicle and light truck alternators use Lundahl or 'claw-pole' field construction.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] This uses a shaped iron core on the rotor to produce a multi-pole field from a single coil winding.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] The poles of the rotor look like fingers of two hands interlocked with each other.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] The coil is mounted axially inside this and field current is supplied by slip rings and carbon brushes.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] These alternators have their field and stator windings cooled by axial airflow, produced by an external fan attached to the drive belt pulley.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Modern vehicles now use the compact alternator layout.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] This is electrically and magnetically similar, but has improved air cooling.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Better cooling permits more power from a smaller machine.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] The casing has distinctive radial vent slots at each end and now encloses the fan.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Two fans are used, one at each end, and the airflow is semi-radial, entering axially and leaving radially outwards.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] The stator windings now consist of a dense central band where the iron core and copper windings are tightly packed, and end bands where the windings are more exposed for better heat transfer.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] The closer core spacing from the rotor improves magnetic efficiency.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] The smaller, enclosed fans produce less noise, particularly at higher machine speeds.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Alternators can also be water-cooled in cars.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Larger vehicles may have field coil alternators similar to larger machines.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] The windings of a 3 phase alternator may be connected using either the *delta* or *star* (*wye*) connection regime set-up.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Brushless versions of these type alternators are also common in larger machinery such as highway trucks and earthmoving machinery.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] With two oversized shaft bearings as the only wearing parts, these can provide extremely long and reliable service, even exceeding the engine overhaul intervals.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators require a voltage regulator which operates by modulating the small field current to produce a constant voltage at the battery terminals.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Early designs (c.1960s–1970s) used a discrete device mounted elsewhere in the vehicle.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Intermediate designs (c.1970s–1990s) incorporated the voltage regulator into the alternator housing.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Modern designs do away with the voltage regulator altogether; voltage regulation is now a function of the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] The field current is much smaller than the output current of the alternator; for example, a 70 A alternator may need only 2-3 A of field current.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] The field current is supplied to the rotor windings by slip rings.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] The low current and relatively smooth slip rings ensure greater reliability and longer life than that obtained by a DC generator with its commutator and higher current being passed through its brushes.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] The field windings are supplied with power from the battery via the ignition switch and regulator.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] A parallel circuit supplies the "charge" warning indicator and is earthed via the regulator (which is why the indicator is on when the ignition is on but the engine is not running).
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Once the engine is running and the alternator is generating power, a diode feeds the field current from the alternator main output equalizing the voltage across the warning indicator which goes off.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] The wire supplying the field current is often referred to as the "exciter" wire.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] The drawback of this arrangement is that if the warning lamp burns out or the "exciter" wire is disconnected, no current reaches the field windings and the alternator will not generate power.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Some warning indicator circuits are equipped with a resistor in parallel with the lamp that permit excitation current to flow if the warning lamp burns out.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] The driver should check that the warning indicator is on when the engine is stopped; otherwise, there might not be any indication of a failure of the belt which may also drive the cooling water pump.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Some alternators will self-excite when the engine reaches a certain speed.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] In recent years, alternator regulators are linked to the vehicle's computer system and various factors including air temperature obtained from the intake air temperature sensor, battery temperature sensor and engine load are evaluated in adjusting the voltage supplied by the alternator.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Older automobiles with minimal lighting may have had an alternator capable of producing only 30 amperes.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger car and light truck alternators are rated around 50–70 A, though higher ratings are becoming more common, especially as there is more load on the vehicle's electrical system with air conditioning, electric power steering and other electrical systems.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators used on buses, heavy equipment or emergency vehicles may produce 300 A.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Semi-trucks usually have alternators which output 140 A.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators may be water-cooled or oil-cooled.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Efficiency of automotive alternators is limited by fan cooling loss, bearing loss, iron loss, copper loss, and the voltage drop in the diode bridges.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Efficiency reduces dramatically at high speeds mainly due to fan resistance.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] At medium speeds efficiency of today's alternators is 70–80%.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] This betters very small high-performance permanent magnet alternators, such as those used for bicycle lighting systems, which achieve an efficiency around 60%.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Larger permanent magnet electric machines (that can operate as motors or alternators) can achieve today much higher efficiencies.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Pellegrino et al., for instance, propose not particularly expensive designs that show ample regions in which efficiency is above 96%.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Large AC generators used in power stations run at carefully controlled speeds and have no constraints on size or weight.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] They have very high efficiencies as high as 98%.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] Hybrid electric vehicles replace the separate alternator and starter motor with one or more combined motor/generator(s) that start the internal combustion engine, provide some or all of the mechanical power to the wheels, and charge a large storage battery.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] When more than one motor/generator is present, as in the Hybrid Synergy Drive used in the Toyota Prius and others, one may operate as a generator and feed the other as a motor, providing an electromechanical path for some of the engine power to flow to the wheels.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator-automotive] These motor/generators have considerably more powerful electronic devices for their control than the automotive alternator described above.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] An **alternator** (or **synchronous generator**) is an electrical generator that converts mechanical energy to electrical energy in the form of alternating current (AC).
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] For reasons of cost and simplicity, most alternators use a rotating magnetic field with a stationary armature.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] The rotor coil is externally excited by a small direct current (DC), while the AC is generated in the stationary coils.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Occasionally, a linear alternator or a rotating armature with a stationary magnetic field is used.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Although any AC electrical generator might be called an alternator, usually the term refers to small rotating machines driven by automotive and other internal combustion engines.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] The term usually applies those types with externally excited rotor coils.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] An alternator that uses a permanent magnet for its magnetic field is called a magneto.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Alternators in power stations driven by steam turbines are called turbo-alternators.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Large 50 or 60 Hz three-phase alternators in power plants generate most of the world's electric power, which is distributed by electric power grids.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Alternating current generating systems were known in simple forms from the discovery of the magnetic induction of electric current in the 1830s.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Rotating generators naturally produced alternating current, but since there was little use for it, it was normally converted into direct current via the addition of a commutator in the generator.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] The early machines were developed by pioneers such as Michael Faraday and Hippolyte Pixii.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Faraday developed the "rotating rectangle", whose operation was *heteropolar* – each active conductor passed successively through regions where the magnetic field was in opposite directions.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Lord Kelvin and Sebastian Ferranti also developed early alternators, producing frequencies between 100 and 300 Hz.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] The late 1870s saw the introduction of the first large-scale electrical systems with central generation stations to power Arc lamps, used to light whole streets, factory yards, or the interior of large warehouses.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Some, such as Yablochkov arc lamps introduced in 1878, ran better on alternating current, and the development of these early AC generating systems was accompanied by the first use of the word "alternator".
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Supplying the proper amount of voltage from generating stations in these early systems was left up to the engineer's skill in "riding the load".
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] In 1883 the Ganz Works invented the constant voltage generator that could produce a stated output voltage, regardless of the value of the actual load.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] The introduction of transformers in the mid-1880s led to the widespread use of alternating current and the use of alternators needed to produce it.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] After 1891, polyphase alternators were introduced to supply currents of multiple differing phases.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Later alternators were designed for various alternating current frequencies between sixteen and about one hundred hertz for use with arc lighting, incandescent lighting, and electric motors.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Specialized radio frequency alternators like the Alexanderson alternator were developed as longwave radio transmitters around World War 1 and used in a few high power wireless telegraphy stations before vacuum tube transmitters replaced them.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] A conductor moving relative to a magnetic field develops an electromotive force (EMF) in it (Faraday's Law).
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] This EMF reverses its polarity when it moves under magnetic poles of opposite polarity.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Typically, a rotating magnet, called the rotor, turns within a stationary set of conductors, called the stator, wound in coils on an iron core.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] The field cuts across the conductors, generating an induced EMF (electromotive force), as the mechanical input causes the rotor to turn.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] The rotating magnetic field induces an AC voltage in the stator windings.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Since the currents in the stator windings vary in step with the position of the rotor, an alternator is a synchronous generator.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] The rotor's magnetic field may be produced by permanent magnets or by a field coil electromagnet.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Automotive alternators use a rotor winding, which allows control of the alternator's generated voltage by varying the current in the rotor field winding.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Permanent magnet machines avoid the loss due to magnetizing current in the rotor, but are restricted in size due to the cost of the magnet material.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Since the permanent magnet field is constant, the terminal voltage varies directly with the speed of the generator.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Brushless AC generators are usually larger than those used in automotive applications.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] An automatic voltage control device controls the field current to keep the output voltage constant.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] If the output voltage from the stationary armature coils drops due to an increase in demand, more current is fed into the rotating field coils through the voltage regulator (VR).
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] This increases the magnetic field around the field coils, which induces a greater voltage in the armature coils.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Thus, the output voltage is brought back up to its original value.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Alternators used in central power stations also control the field current to regulate reactive power and to help stabilize the power system against the effects of momentary faults.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Often, there are three sets of stator windings, physically offset so that the rotating magnetic field produces a three-phase current, displaced by one-third of a period with respect to each other.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] One cycle of alternating current is produced each time a pair of field poles passes over a point on the stationary winding.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] The relation between speed and frequency is $N=120f/P$ , where f is the frequency in Hz (cycles per second).
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] P is the number of poles (2, 4, 6, ...), and N is the rotational speed in revolutions per minute (r/min).
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Old descriptions of alternating current systems sometimes give the frequency in terms of alternations per minute, counting each half-cycle as one *alternation*; so 12,000 alternations per minute corresponds to 100 Hz.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] An alternator's output frequency depends on the number of poles and the rotational speed.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] The speed corresponding to a particular frequency is called the *synchronous speed*.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Alternators may be classified by the method of excitation, number of phases, the type of rotation, cooling method, and their application.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] There are two main ways to produce the magnetic field used in the alternators: by using permanent magnets, which create their persistent magnetic field, or by using field coils.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] The alternators that use permanent magnets are specifically called magnetos.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] In other alternators, wound field coils form an electromagnet to produce the rotating magnetic field.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] A device that uses permanent magnets to produce alternating current is called a permanent magnet alternator (PMA).
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] A permanent magnet generator (PMG) may produce either alternating current or direct current if it has a commutator.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] This method of excitation consists of a smaller direct-current (DC) generator fixed on the same shaft as the alternator.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] The DC generator generates a small amount of electricity, just enough to *excite* the field coils of the connected alternator to generate electricity.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] A variation of this system is a type of alternator that uses direct current from a battery for initial excitation upon start-up, after which the alternator becomes self-excited.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] This method of excitation consists of a smaller alternating-current (AC) generator fixed on the same shaft as the alternator.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] The AC stator generates a small amount of field coil excitation current, which is induced in the rotor and rectified to DC by a bridge rectifier built in to the windings where it excites the field coils of the larger connected alternator to generate electricity.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] This system has the advantage of not requiring brushes, which increases service life, although with a slightly lower overall efficiency.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] This method depends on residual magnetism retained in the iron core to generate a weak magnetic field, which would allow a weak voltage to be generated.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] This voltage is used to excite the field coils so the alternator can generate stronger voltage as part of its *build up* process.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] After the initial AC voltage buildup, the field is supplied with rectified voltage from the alternator.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] A brushless alternator is composed of two alternators built end-to-end on one shaft.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Until 1966, alternators used brushes with rotating field.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] With the advancement in semiconductor technology, brushless alternators are possible.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Smaller brushless alternators may look like one unit, but the two parts are readily identifiable in the large versions.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] The main alternator is the larger of the two sections, and the smaller one is the exciter.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] The exciter has stationary field coils and a rotating armature (power coils).
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] The main alternator uses the opposite configuration with a rotating field and stationary armature.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] A bridge rectifier, called the rotating rectifier assembly, is mounted on the rotor.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Neither brushes nor slip rings are used, which reduces the number of wearing parts.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] The main alternator has a rotating field and a stationary armature (power generation windings).
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Varying the amount of current through the stationary exciter field coils varies the 3-phase output from the exciter.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] This output is rectified by a rotating rectifier assembly mounted on the rotor, and the resultant DC supplies the rotating field of the main alternator and hence alternator output.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] The result is that a small DC exciter current indirectly controls the output of the main alternator.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Another way to classify alternators is by the number of phases of their output voltage.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] The output can be single-phase or polyphase.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Three-phase alternators are the most common, but polyphase alternators can be two-phase, six-phase, or more.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] The revolving part of alternators can be the armature or the magnetic field.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] The revolving armature type has the armature wound on the rotor, where the winding moves through a stationary magnetic field.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] The revolving armature type is not often used.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] The revolving field type has a magnetic field on the rotor to rotate through a stationary armature winding.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] The stationary armature can be wound for any convenient medium voltage level, up to tens of thousands of volts; manufacture of slip ring connections for more than a few thousand volts is costly and inconvenient.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Many alternators are cooled by ambient air, forced through the enclosure by an attached fan on the shaft that drives the alternator.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] In vehicles such as transit buses, a heavy demand on the electrical system may require a large alternator to be oil-cooled.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] In marine applications water-cooling is also used.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Expensive automobiles may use water-cooled alternators to meet high electrical system demands.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Most power generation stations use synchronous machines as their generators.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] The connection of these generators to the utility grid requires synchronization conditions to be met.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Synchronous generators provide several important system services.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Their inherent rotational inertia slows the initial frequency decline after a sudden loss of generation, allowing turbine governors and other frequency-control reserves time to respond and restore balance.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] This role is increasingly significant as the share of non-synchronous generation, such as solar photovoltaics and many modern wind plants, grows in many power systems.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Alternators are used in modern internal combustion engine automobiles to charge the battery and to power the electrical system when its engine is running.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] With the availability of affordable silicon-diode rectifiers, alternators were used instead.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] In later diesel–electric locomotives and diesel–electric multiple units, the prime mover turns an alternator which provides electricity for the traction motors (AC or DC).
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] The traction alternator usually incorporates integral silicon diode rectifiers to provide the traction motors with up to 1,200 volts DC.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] The first diesel electric locomotives, and many of those still in service, use DC generators as, before silicon power electronics, it was easier to control the speed of DC traction motors.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Most of these had two generators: one to generate the excitation current for a larger main generator.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Optionally, the generator also supplies head-end power (HEP) or power for electric train heating.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] The HEP option requires a constant engine speed, typically 900 r/min for a 480 V 60 Hz HEP application, even when the locomotive is not moving.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Marine alternators used in yachts are similar to automotive alternators, with appropriate adaptations to the salt-water environment.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Marine alternators are designed to be explosion proof (ignition protected) so that brush sparking will not ignite explosive gas mixtures in an engine room environment.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Depending on the type of system installed, they may be 12 or 24 volts.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Larger marine diesels may have two or more alternators to cope with the heavy electrical demand of a modern yacht.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] On single alternator circuits, the power may be split between the engine starting battery and the domestic or house battery (or batteries) by use of a split-charge diode (battery isolator) or a voltage-sensitive relay.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Due to the high cost of large house battery banks, Marine alternators generally use external regulators.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Multistep regulators control the field current to maximize the charging effectiveness (time to charge) and battery life.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Multistep regulators can be programmed for different battery types.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Two temperature sensors can be added: one for the battery to adjust the charging voltage and an over-temperature sensor on the actual alternator to protect it from overheating.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] High-frequency alternators of the variable-reluctance type were applied commercially to radio transmission in low-frequency radio bands.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] These were used for transmitting Morse code and, experimentally, for transmitting voice and music.
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] In the Alexanderson alternator, both the field winding and armature winding are stationary, and current is induced in the armature by the changing magnetic reluctance of the rotor (which has no windings or current-carrying parts).
[src:alternator-automotive/alternator] Such machines were made to produce radio frequency current for radio transmissions, although the efficiency was low.
[src:alternator-automotive/ampere] The **ampere** (/ˈæmpɛər/ ⓘ *AM-pair*, US: /ˈæmpɪər/ ⓘ *AM-peer*; symbol: **A**), often shortened to **amp**, is the unit of electric current in the International System of Units (SI).
[src:alternator-automotive/ampere] One ampere is equal to 1 coulomb (C) moving past a point per second.
[src:alternator-automotive/ampere] It is named after French mathematician and physicist André-Marie Ampère (1775–1836), considered the father of electromagnetism along with Danish physicist Hans Christian Ørsted.
[src:alternator-automotive/ampere] Prior to the redefinition, the ampere was defined as the current passing through two parallel wires 1 metre apart that produces a magnetic force of 2×10−7 newtons per metre.
[src:alternator-automotive/ampere] The earlier CGS system has two units of current, one structured similarly to the SI's and the other using Coulomb's law as a fundamental relationship, with the CGS unit of charge defined by measuring the force between two charged metal plates.
[src:alternator-automotive/ampere] The CGS unit of current is then defined as one unit of charge per second.
[src:alternator-automotive/ampere] The ampere is named for French physicist and mathematician André-Marie Ampère (1775–1836), who studied electromagnetism and laid the foundation of electrodynamics.
[src:alternator-automotive/ampere] In recognition of Ampère's contributions to the creation of modern electrical science, an international convention, signed at the 1881 International Exposition of Electricity, established the ampere as a standard unit of electrical measurement for electric current.
[src:alternator-automotive/ampere] The ampere was originally defined as one tenth of the unit of electric current in the centimetre–gram–second system of units.
[src:alternator-automotive/ampere] That unit, now known as the abampere, was defined as the amount of current that generates a force of two dynes per centimetre of length between two wires one centimetre apart.
[src:alternator-automotive/ampere] The size of the unit was chosen so that the units derived from it in the MKSA system would be conveniently sized.
[src:alternator-automotive/ampere] The "international ampere" was an early realisation of the ampere, defined as the current that would deposit 0.001118 grams of silver per second from a silver nitrate solution.
[src:alternator-automotive/ampere] Later, more accurate measurements revealed that this current is 0.99985 A.
[src:alternator-automotive/ampere] Since power is defined as the product of current and voltage, the ampere can alternatively be expressed in terms of the other units using the relationship *I* = *P*/*V*, and thus 1 A = 1 W/V.
[src:alternator-automotive/ampere] Current can be measured by a multimeter, a device that can measure electrical voltage, current, and resistance.
[src:alternator-automotive/ampere] Ampère's force law states that there is an attractive or repulsive force between two parallel wires carrying an electric current.
[src:alternator-automotive/ampere] This force was used in the formal definition of the ampere, giving the vacuum magnetic permeability (magnetic constant, *μ*0) a value of exactly 4π × 10−7 henries per metre (H/m, equivalent to N/A2).
[src:alternator-automotive/ampere] The SI unit of charge, the coulomb, was then defined as "the quantity of electricity carried in 1 second by a current of 1 ampere".
[src:alternator-automotive/ampere] In general, charge Q was determined by steady current I flowing for a time t as *Q* = *It*.
[src:alternator-automotive/ampere] Techniques to establish the realisation of an ampere had a relative uncertainty of approximately a few parts in 107, and involved realisations of the watt, the ohm and the volt.
[src:alternator-automotive/ampere] The SI unit of charge, the coulomb, "is the quantity of electricity carried in 1 second by a current of 1 ampere".
[src:alternator-automotive/ampere] The relation of the ampere (A = C/s) to the coulomb (C) is the same as that of the watt (W = J/s) to the joule (J).
[src:alternator-automotive/ampere] These SI derived units can either be given special names e.g. watt, volt, lux, etc. or defined in terms of others, e.g. metre per second.
[src:alternator-automotive/ampere] There are also some SI units that are frequently used in the context of electrical engineering and electrical appliances, but are defined independently of the ampere, notably the hertz, joule, watt, candela, lumen, and lux.
[src:alternator-automotive/ampere] Like other SI units, the ampere can be modified by adding a prefix that multiplies it by a power of 10.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] A **car**, or an **automobile**, is a motor vehicle with wheels.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Most definitions of cars state that they run primarily on roads, seat 1-8 people, have four wheels, and mainly transport people rather than cargo.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] There are over 1.6 billion cars in use worldwide as of 2025.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The French inventor Nicolas-Joseph Cugnot built the first steam-powered road vehicle in 1769, while the Swiss inventor François Isaac de Rivaz designed and constructed the first internal combustion-powered automobile in 1808.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The modern car—a practical, marketable automobile for everyday use—was invented in 1886, when the German inventor Carl Benz patented his Benz Patent-Motorwagen.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Commercial cars became widely available during the 20th century.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The 1901 Oldsmobile Curved Dash and the 1908 Ford Model T, both American cars, are widely considered the first mass-produced and mass-affordable cars, respectively.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Cars were rapidly adopted in the US, where they replaced horse-drawn carriages.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] In Europe and other parts of the world, demand for automobiles did not increase until after World War II.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] In the 21st century, car usage is still increasing rapidly, especially in China, India, and other newly industrialised countries.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Cars have controls for driving, parking, passenger comfort, and a variety of lamps.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Over the decades, additional features and controls have been added to vehicles, making them progressively more complex.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] These include rear-reversing cameras, air conditioning, navigation systems, and in-car entertainment.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Most cars in use in the early 2020s are propelled by an internal combustion engine, fueled by the combustion of fossil fuels.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Electric cars, which were invented early in the history of the car, became commercially available in the 2000s and widespread in the 2020s.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The transition from fossil-fuel-powered cars to electric cars is a central feature of most climate change mitigation scenarios.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] There are costs and benefits to car use.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The costs to the individual include acquiring the vehicle, interest payments (if the car is financed), repairs and maintenance, fuel, depreciation, driving time, parking fees, taxes, and insurance.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The costs to society include resources used to produce cars and fuel, maintaining roads, land-use, road congestion, air pollution, noise pollution, public health, and disposing of the vehicle at the end of its life.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Traffic collisions are the largest cause of injury-related deaths worldwide.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Personal benefits include on-demand transportation, mobility, independence, and convenience.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Societal benefits include economic benefits, such as job and wealth creation from the automotive industry, transportation provision, and societal wellbeing from leisure and travel opportunities.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] People's ability to move flexibly from place to place has far-reaching implications for society.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The English word *car* is believed to originate from Latin *carrus*/*carrum* "wheeled vehicle" or (via Old North French) Middle English **carre** "two-wheeled cart", both of which in turn derive from Gaulish **karros** "chariot".
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] It originally referred to any wheeled horse-drawn vehicle, such as a cart, carriage, or wagon.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The word also occurs in other Celtic languages.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] "Motor car", attested from 1895, is the usual formal term in British English.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] "Autocar", a variant likewise attested from 1895 and literally meaning "self-propelled car", is now considered archaic.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] "Horseless carriage" is attested from 1895.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] "Automobile", a classical compound derived from Ancient Greek **autós** (αὐτός) "self" and Latin **mobilis** "movable", entered English from French and was first adopted by the Automobile Club of Great Britain in 1897.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] It fell out of favour in Britain and is now used chiefly in North America, where the abbreviated form "auto" commonly appears as an adjective in compound formations like "auto industry" and "auto mechanic".
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] In 1649, Hans Hautsch of Nuremberg built a clockwork-driven carriage.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The first steam-powered vehicle was designed by Ferdinand Verbiest, a Flemish member of a Jesuit mission in China around 1672.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] It was a 65-centimetre-long (26 in) scale-model toy for the Kangxi Emperor that was unable to carry a driver or a passenger.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] It is not known with certainty if Verbiest's model was successfully built or run.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Nicolas-Joseph Cugnot is widely credited with building the first full-scale, self-propelled mechanical vehicle in about 1769; he created a steam-powered tricycle.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] He also constructed two steam tractors for the French Army, one of which is preserved in the French National Conservatory of Arts and Crafts.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] His inventions were limited by problems with water supply and maintaining steam pressure.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] In 1801, Richard Trevithick built and demonstrated his Puffing Devil road locomotive, believed by many to be the first demonstration of a steam-powered road vehicle.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] It was unable to maintain sufficient steam pressure for long periods and was of little practical use.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The development of external combustion (also known as steam) engines is detailed in the history of the car.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Still, it is often treated separately from the development of cars in their modern understanding.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] A variety of steam-powered road vehicles were used during the first part of the 19th century, including steam cars, steam buses, phaetons, and steam rollers.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] In the United Kingdom, sentiment against them led to the Locomotive Acts of 1865.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] In 1807, Nicéphore Niépce and his brother Claude created what was probably the world's first internal combustion engine (which they called a Pyréolophore), but installed it in a boat on the river Saone in France.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Coincidentally, in 1807, the Swiss inventor François Isaac de Rivaz designed his own "de Rivaz internal combustion engine", and used it to develop the world's first vehicle to be powered by such an engine.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The Niépces' Pyréolophore was fuelled by a mixture of Lycopodium powder (dried spores of the Lycopodium plant), finely crushed coal dust, and resin that were mixed with oil, whereas de Rivaz used a mixture of hydrogen and oxygen.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Neither design was successful, as was the case with others, such as Samuel Brown, Samuel Morey, and Etienne Lenoir, who each built vehicles (usually adapted carriages or carts) powered by internal combustion engines.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] In November 1881, French inventor Gustave Trouvé demonstrated a three-wheeled car powered by electricity at the International Exposition of Electricity.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Several other German engineers, including Gottlieb Daimler, Wilhelm Maybach, Siegfried Marcus, and Carl Benz were also working on cars and engines at about the same time.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] In 1879, Benz was granted a patent for a stationary engine.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] He had long dreamed of applying the internal combustion engine to produce a horseless carriage and began work on it in 1884.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] In 1885 he produced his first prototype car, the Benz Patent-Motorwagen Nr.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] On 29 January 1886 he applied for a patent for it, which was granted on 2 November of that year.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Benz further developed the Patent-Motorwagen, and had sufficient confidence in this to drive into Mannheim and have his vehicle written up in the *Neue Badische Landeszeitung* of 4 June 1886.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Benz' first production car, the Patent-Motorwagen Model 2, was produced in single-digit numbers in 1887–88.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Frenchman Émile Roger, already producing Benz engines under license, had added the Benz car to his product line in 1888.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Perhaps 60 of the Model 3 were produced between 1889 and 1893, the majority assembled in Paris from kits by Émile Roger.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Many historians consider Benz' advances so significant that they largely credit him as the inventor of the car and regard his 1886 patent as the birth of the modern car.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] In August 1888, Bertha Benz, the wife and business partner of Carl Benz, undertook the first road trip by an internal combustion engine car, to prove the road-worthiness of her husband's invention.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] In 1896, Carl Benz designed and patented the first internal-combustion flat engine, called *boxermotor*.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] During the last years of the 19th century, Benz was the largest car company in the world with 572 units produced in 1899 and, because of its size, Benz & Cie. became a joint-stock company.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The first motor car in central Europe and one of the first factory-made cars in the world was produced by the Czech company Nesselsdorfer Wagenbau (later renamed to Tatra) in 1897, the Präsident automobil.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Daimler and Maybach founded Daimler Motoren Gesellschaft (DMG) in Cannstatt in 1890, and sold their first car in 1892 under the brand name *Daimler*.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] It was a horse-drawn stagecoach built by another manufacturer, which they retrofitted with an engine of their design.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] By 1895, about 30 vehicles had been built by Daimler and Maybach, either at the Daimler works or at the Hotel Hermann, where they set up shop after disputes with their backers.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Benz, Maybach, and the Daimler team seem to have been unaware of each other's early work.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] They never worked together; by the time of the merger of the two companies, Daimler and Maybach were no longer part of DMG.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Daimler died in 1900, and later that year, Maybach designed an engine named *Daimler-Mercedes* that was installed in a specially ordered model built to specifications set by Emil Jellinek.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] This was a limited production run of vehicles for Jellinek to race and market in his country.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Two years later, in 1902, a new model of the DMG car was produced and named Mercedes after the Maybach engine, which generated 35 hp.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Maybach left DMG shortly thereafter and opened his own business.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Rights to the *Daimler* brand name were sold to other manufacturers.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] In 1890, Émile Levassor (who had bought a Benz Patent-Motorwagen Model 2 in 1888) and Armand Peugeot of France began producing vehicles with Daimler engines, and so laid the foundation of the automotive industry in France.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] In 1891, Auguste Doriot and his Peugeot colleague Louis Rigoulot completed the longest trip by a petrol-driven vehicle when their self-designed and built Daimler-powered Peugeot Type 3 completed 2,100 kilometres (1,300 mi) from Valentigney to Paris and Brest and back again.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] They were attached to the first Paris–Brest–Paris bicycle race, but finished six days after the winning cyclist, Charles Terront.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The first design for an American car with a petrol internal combustion engine was made in 1877 by George Selden of Rochester, New York.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Selden applied for a patent for a car in 1879, but the patent application expired because the vehicle was never built.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] After a delay of 16 years and a series of attachments to his application, on 5 November 1895, Selden was granted a US patent (U.S. patent 549,160) for a two-stroke car engine, which hindered, more than encouraged, development of cars in the United States.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] His patent was challenged by Henry Ford and others, and overturned in 1911.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] In 1893, the first running, petrol-driven American car was built and road-tested by the Duryea brothers of Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The first public run of the Duryea Motor Wagon took place on 21 September 1893, on Taylor Street in Metro Center Springfield.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Studebaker, subsidiary of a long-established wagon and coach manufacturer, started to build cars in 1897 and commenced sales of electric vehicles in 1902 and petrol vehicles in 1904.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] In Britain, there had been several attempts to build steam cars with varying degrees of success, with Thomas Rickett even attempting a production run in 1860.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Santler from Malvern is recognised by the Veteran Car Club of Great Britain as having made the first petrol-driven car in the country in 1894, followed by Frederick William Lanchester in 1895, but these were both one-offs.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The first production vehicles in Great Britain came from the Daimler Company, a company founded by Harry J.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Lawson in 1896, after purchasing the right to use the name of the engines.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Lawson's company made its first car in 1897, and they bore the name Daimler.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] In 1892, German engineer Rudolf Diesel was granted a patent for a "New Rational Combustion Engine".
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] In 1897, he built the first diesel engine.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Steam-, electric-, and petrol-driven vehicles competed for a few decades, with petrol internal combustion engines achieving dominance in the 1910s.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Although various pistonless rotary engine designs have attempted to compete with the conventional piston and crankshaft design, only Mazda's version of the Wankel engine has had more than very limited success.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] All in all, it is estimated that over 100,000 patents have contributed to the modern automobile and motorcycle.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Large-scale, production-line manufacturing of affordable cars was started by Ransom Olds in 1901 at his Oldsmobile factory in Lansing, Michigan, and based upon stationary assembly line techniques pioneered by Marc Isambard Brunel at the Portsmouth Block Mills, England, in 1802.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The assembly line style of mass production and interchangeable parts had been pioneered in the US by Thomas Blanchard in 1821, at the Springfield Armory in Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] This concept was greatly expanded by Henry Ford, beginning in 1913 with the world's first *moving* assembly line for cars at the Highland Park Ford Plant.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] As a result, Ford's cars came off the line in 15-minute intervals, much faster than previous methods, increasing productivity eightfold while using less labour (from 12.5 manhours to 1 hour 33 minutes).
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] It was so successful, paint became a bottleneck.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Only Japan black would dry fast enough, forcing the company to drop the variety of colours available before 1913, until fast-drying Duco lacquer was developed in 1926.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] This is the source of Ford's apocryphal remark, "any color as long as it's black".
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] In 1914, an assembly line worker could buy a Model T with four months' pay.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Ford's complex safety procedures—especially assigning each worker to a specific location rather than allowing them to roam—dramatically reduced injury rates.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The combination of high wages and high efficiency is called "Fordism" and was copied by most major industries.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The efficiency gains from the assembly line also coincided with the US's economic rise.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The assembly line forced workers to move at a certain pace with very repetitive motions, which led to more output per worker, while other countries used less productive methods.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] In the automotive industry, its success was dominant and quickly spread worldwide, with the founding of Ford France and Ford Britain in 1911, Ford Denmark in 1923, and Ford Germany in 1925; in 1921, Citroën was the first native European manufacturer to adopt the production method.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Soon, companies had to have assembly lines or risk going bankrupt; by 1930, 250 companies that did not have assembly lines disappeared.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The development of automotive technology was rapid, due in part to the hundreds of small manufacturers competing to gain the world's attention.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Key developments included electric ignition and the electric self-starter (both by Charles Kettering, for the Cadillac Motor Company in 1910–1911), independent suspension, and four-wheel brakes.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Since the 1920s, nearly all cars have been mass-produced to meet market needs, so marketing plans have often heavily influenced car design.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Sloan who established the idea of different makes of cars produced by one company, called the General Motors Companion Make Program, so that buyers could "move up" as their fortunes improved.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Reflecting the rapid pace of change, makers shared parts with one another, resulting in lower costs across all price ranges.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Most British small-car assemblers, from Abbey to Xtra, had gone under.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Citroën did the same in France, coming to cars in 1919; between them and other cheap cars in reply such as Renault's 10CV and Peugeot's 5CV, they produced 550,000 cars in 1925, and Mors, Hurtu, and others could not compete.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Germany's first mass-manufactured car, the Opel 4PS *Laubfrosch* (Tree Frog), came off the line at Rüsselsheim in 1924, soon making Opel the top car builder in Germany, with 37.5 per cent of the market.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] In Japan, car production was very limited before World War II.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Only a handful of companies produced vehicles in limited numbers, and these were small, three-wheeled for commercial use, like Daihatsu, or the result of partnerships with European companies, like Isuzu building the Wolseley A-9 in 1922.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Mitsubishi was also partnered with Fiat and built the Mitsubishi Model A based on a Fiat vehicle.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Toyota, Nissan, Suzuki, Mazda, and Honda began as companies producing non-automotive products before the war, then switched to car production in the 1950s.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Kiichiro Toyoda's decision to take Toyoda Loom Works into automobile manufacturing would eventually lead to the formation of Toyota Motor Corporation, the world's largest automobile manufacturer.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Subaru, meanwhile, was formed from a conglomerate of six companies that banded together as Fuji Heavy Industries, as a result of having been broken up under *keiretsu* legislation.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Most cars in use in the mid 2020s run on petrol burnt in an internal combustion engine (ICE).
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Some cities ban older, more polluting petrol-driven cars, and some countries plan to ban sales in the future.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] However, some environmental groups say this phase-out of fossil fuel vehicles must be brought forward to limit climate change.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Production of petrol-fuelled cars peaked in 2017.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Other hydrocarbon fossil fuels also burnt by deflagration (rather than detonation) in ICE cars include diesel, autogas, and CNG.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Removal of fossil fuel subsidies, concerns about oil dependence, tightening environmental laws and restrictions on greenhouse gas emissions are propelling work on alternative power systems for cars.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] This includes hybrid vehicles, plug-in electric vehicles, and hydrogen vehicles.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] As of 2025 one in four cars sold is electric but, despite rapid growth, less than one in twenty cars on the world's roads were fully electric and plug-in hybrid cars by the end of 2024.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Cars for racing or speed records have sometimes employed jet or rocket engines, but these are impractical for common use.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Oil consumption has increased rapidly in the 20th and 21st centuries because there are more cars; the 1980s oil glut even fuelled the sales of low-economy vehicles in OECD countries.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] In almost all hybrid (even mild hybrid) and pure electric cars, regenerative braking recovers and returns to a battery some energy which would otherwise be wasted by friction brakes getting hot.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Although all cars must have friction brakes (front disc brakes and either disc or drum rear brakes) for emergency stops, regenerative braking improves efficiency, particularly in city driving.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Cars are equipped with controls for driving, passenger comfort, and safety, normally operated by a combination of feet and hands, and occasionally by voice in 21st-century cars.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] These controls include a steering wheel, pedals for operating the brakes and controlling the car's speed (and, in a manual transmission car, a clutch pedal), a shift lever or stick for changing gears, and several buttons and dials for turning on lights, ventilation, and other functions.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Modern cars' controls are now standardised, such as the location of the accelerator and brake, but this was not always the case.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Controls are evolving in response to new technologies, for example, the electric car and the integration of mobile communications.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Some of the original controls are no longer required.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] For example, all cars once had controls for the choke valve, clutch, ignition timing, and a crank instead of an electric starter.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] However, new controls have also been added to vehicles, making them more complex.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] These include air conditioning, navigation systems, and in-car entertainment.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Another trend is the replacement of physical knobs and switches with secondary controls, such as touchscreen controls, such as BMW's *iDrive* and Ford's *MyFord Touch*.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Another change is that while early cars' pedals were physically linked to the brake mechanism and throttle, in the early 2020s, cars have increasingly replaced these physical linkages with electronic controls.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] More costly upper-class and luxury cars are equipped with features earlier such as massage seats and collision avoidance systems.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Dedicated automotive fuses and circuit breakers prevent damage from electrical overload.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Cars are typically fitted with multiple types of lights.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Interior ceiling lights in the car are usually fitted for the driver and passengers.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Some vehicles also have a boot light and, more rarely, an engine compartment light.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] During the late 20th and early 21st century, cars increased in weight due to batteries, modern steel safety cages, anti-lock brakes, airbags, and "more-powerful—if more efficient—engines" and, as of 2019, typically weigh between 1 and 3 tonnes (1.1 and 3.3 short tons; 0.98 and 2.95 long tons).
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Heavier cars are safer for the driver from a crash perspective, but more dangerous for other vehicles and road users.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The weight of a car influences fuel consumption and performance, with more weight resulting in increased fuel consumption and decreased performance.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The Wuling Hongguang Mini EV, a typical city car, weighs about 700 kilograms (1,500 lb).
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Heavier cars include SUVs and extended-length SUVs like the Suburban.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Some places tax heavier cars more: as well as improving pedestrian safety, this can encourage manufacturers to use materials such as recycled aluminium instead of steel.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] It has been suggested that one benefit of subsidising charging infrastructure is that cars can use lighter batteries.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Most cars are designed to carry multiple occupants, often with four or five seats.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Cars with five seats typically seat two passengers in the front and three in the rear.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Full-size cars and large sport utility vehicles can often carry six, seven, or more occupants, depending on seat arrangement.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] On the other hand, sports cars are most often designed with only two seats.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Utility vehicles like pickup trucks combine seating with extra cargo or utility functionality.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The differing needs for passenger capacity and their luggage or cargo space has resulted in the availability of a large variety of body styles to meet individual consumer requirements that include, among others, the sedan/saloon, hatchback, station wagon/estate, coupe, and minivan.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Mary Ward became one of the first documented car fatalities in 1869 in Parsonstown, Ireland, and Henry Bliss one of the US's first pedestrian car casualties in 1899 in New York City.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] There are now standard tests for safety in new cars, such as the Euro and US NCAP tests, and insurance-industry-backed tests by the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety (IIHS).
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] However, not all such tests consider the safety of people outside the car, such as drivers of other cars, pedestrians and cyclists.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Some countries are tightening safety regulations for new cars, for example to mandate data recorders and automated braking.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The costs of car usage, which may include the cost of: acquiring the vehicle, repairs and auto maintenance, fuel, depreciation, driving time, parking fees, taxes, and insurance, are weighed against the cost of the alternatives, and the value of the benefits—perceived and real—of vehicle usage.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The benefits may include on-demand transportation, mobility, independence, and convenience, and emergency power.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Societal benefits may include economic benefits, such as job and wealth creation, from car production and maintenance, transportation provision, societal wellbeing derived from leisure and travel opportunities, and revenue generation from the tax opportunities.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The ability of humans to move flexibly from place to place has far-reaching implications for the nature of societies.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Trucks' share of US vehicles produced has tripled since 1975.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Though vehicle fuel efficiency has increased within each category, the overall trend toward less efficient types of vehicles has offset some of the benefits of greater fuel economy and reductions in pollution and carbon dioxide emissions.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Without the shift towards SUVs, energy use per unit distance could have fallen 30% more than it did from 2010 to 2022.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Car production and use have a large number of environmental impacts: it causes local air pollution plastic pollution and contributes to greenhouse gas emissions and climate change.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Cars and vans caused 10% of energy-related carbon dioxide emissions in 2022.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] As of 2023, electric cars produce about half the emissions over their lifetime as diesel and petrol cars.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] This is set to improve as countries produce more of their electricity from low-carbon sources.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Cars consume almost a quarter of world oil production as of 2019.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Cities planned around cars are often less dense, which leads to further emissions, as they are less walkable, for instance.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] A growing demand for large SUVs is driving up emissions from cars.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Cars are a major cause of air pollution, which stems from exhaust gas in diesel and petrol cars and from dust from brakes, tyres, and road wear.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Heavy metals and microplastics (from tyres) are also released into the environment, during production, use, and at the end of life.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Mining related to car manufacturing and oil spills both cause water pollution.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Animals and plants are often negatively affected by cars through habitat destruction and fragmentation caused by the road network, as well as pollution.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Animals are also killed every year on roads by cars, referred to as roadkill.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] More recent road developments are including significant environmental mitigation in their designs, such as green bridges (designed to allow wildlife crossings) and creating wildlife corridors.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Governments use fiscal policies, such as road tax, to discourage the purchase and use of more polluting cars; Vehicle emission standards ban the sale of new highly pollution cars.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Many countries plan to stop selling fossil cars altogether between 2025 and 2050.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Various cities have implemented low-emission zones, banning old fossil fuel and Amsterdam is planning to ban fossil fuel cars completely.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Some cities make it easier for people to choose other forms of transport, such as cycling.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Many Chinese cities limit licensing of fossil fuel cars.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Mass production of personal motor vehicles in the United States and other developed countries with extensive territories, such as Australia, Argentina, and France, vastly increased individual and group mobility and greatly expanded economic development in urban, suburban, exurban, and rural areas.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Growth in the popularity of cars and commuting has led to traffic congestion.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Moscow, Istanbul, Bogotá, Mexico City and São Paulo were the world's most congested cities in 2018 according to INRIX, a data analytics company.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] In the United States, the transport divide and car dependency resulting from domination of car-based transport systems presents barriers to employment in low-income neighbourhoods, with many low-income individuals and families forced to run cars they cannot afford in order to maintain their income.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Dependency on automobiles by African Americans may result in exposure to the hazards of driving while black and other types of racial discrimination related to buying, financing and insuring them.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Air pollution from cars increases the risk of a number of diseases, including stroke, heart disease, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), lung cancer, respiratory infections and aggravated asthma.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Air pollution is also linked to global impacts on all aspects of sexual reproduction from male and female fertility to fetal development, birth outcomes, and long-term health of offspring.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Children are extra vulnerable to air pollution, as their bodies are still developing and air pollution in children is linked to the development of asthma, childhood cancer, and neurocognitive issues such as autism.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The growth in popularity of the car allowed cities to sprawl, therefore encouraging more travel by car, resulting in inactivity and obesity, which in turn can lead to increased risk of a variety of diseases.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] When places are designed around cars, children have fewer opportunities to go places by themselves and lose opportunities to become more independent.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Intensive development of conventional battery electric vehicles is continuing into the 2020s, for example lithium iron phosphate batteries are safer and cheaper.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Other car technologies that are under development include wireless charging.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Software is increasing and may have many new uses, for example automatically not hitting pedestrians.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] New materials which may replace steel car bodies include aluminium, fibreglass, carbon fibre, biocomposites, and carbon nanotubes.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Telematics technology is allowing more and more people to share cars, on a pay-as-you-go basis, through car share and carpool schemes.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Communication is also evolving due to connected car systems.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Microwave weapons which can disable cars are being tested.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Fully self-driving vehicles, also known as autonomous cars, already exist as robotaxis in some locations.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Laws for the regulation of self-driving cars will need updating before widespread deployment can happen.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Car-share arrangements and carpooling are also increasingly popular, in the US and Europe.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Services like car sharing offer residents to "share" a vehicle rather than own a car in already congested neighbourhoods.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The automotive industry designs, develops, manufactures, markets, and sells the world's motor vehicles, more than three-quarters of which are cars.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] In 2020, there were 56 million cars manufactured worldwide, down from 67 million the previous year.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The automotive industry in China produces by far the most (20 million in 2020), followed by Japan (seven million), then Germany, South Korea, and India.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The largest market is China, followed by the US.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] There are around 1.644 billion cars in use worldwide as of January 2025; they burn over a trillion litres (0.26×10^12 US gal; 0.22×10^12 imp gal) of petrol and diesel fuel yearly, consuming about 50 exajoules (14,000 TWh) of energy.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The number of cars is increasing rapidly in China and India.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] In the opinion of some, urban transport systems based around the car have proved unsustainable, consuming excessive energy, affecting the health of populations, and delivering a declining level of service despite increasing investment.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Many of these negative effects fall disproportionately on those social groups who are also least likely to own and drive cars.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The sustainable transport movement focuses on solutions to these problems.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] The car industry is also facing increasing competition from the public transport sector, as some people re-evaluate their use of private vehicles.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] In July 2021, the European Commission introduced the "Fit for 55" legislation package, outlining crucial directives for the automotive sector's future.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] According to this package, by 2035, all newly sold cars in the European market must be Zero-emissions vehicles.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Established alternatives for some aspects of car use include public transport such as busses, trolleybusses, trains, subways, tramways, light rail, cycling, and walking.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Bicycle sharing systems have been established in China and many European cities, including Copenhagen and Amsterdam.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Similar programmes have been developed in large US cities.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Additional individual modes of transport, such as personal rapid transit could serve as an alternative to cars if they prove to be socially accepted.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] A study which checked the costs and the benefits of introducing Low Traffic Neighbourhood in London found the benefits overpass the costs approximately by 100 times in the first 20 years and the difference is growing over time.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] Motorsport is a sport involving high speed racing and drifting.
[src:alternator-automotive/automobile] It includes various racing series such as Formula One, IndyCar Series, NASCAR, World Rally Championship and MotoGP.
